<PageLayout
  title="PL-8177: the oral melanocortin trying to calm inflammation from inside the gut"
  kicker="Investigational"
  description="PL-8177 is Palatin's investigational oral MC1R agonist for inflammatory bowel disease. Its clever trick: it's a peptide that works without being absorbed, acting on the colon lining directly — a drug built from the melanocortin system's own anti-inflammatory role."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'PL-8177', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 1 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_1_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Ulcerative colitis', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulcerative_colitis'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'PL-8177 is Palatin’s investigational oral, selective MC1R agonist — a cyclic peptide being developed for inflammatory bowel disease.',
      'It is built from the melanocortin system’s natural anti-inflammatory role: activating MC1R helps switch off inflammation, and PL-8177 aims that effect at the gut.',
      'It is oral without being absorbed — formulated to act locally on the colon lining with essentially no systemic exposure, sidestepping the usual oral-peptide problem.',
      'A Phase 2 ulcerative colitis study reported positive topline remission and response signals, but was cut short (12 patients) as Palatin refocused on obesity, so it was underpowered for significance.',
      'It represents the third major melanocortin frontier beyond pigment and appetite: inflammation.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    PL-8177 is a good reminder that the melanocortin system does more than pigment and
    appetite. Its third great role is <strong>calming inflammation</strong> — the natural
    signal <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a> is a potent anti-inflammatory molecule — and
    PL-8177 is an attempt to turn that biology into a drug for inflammatory bowel
    disease.<Cite n={3} /> It is one of Palatin Technologies' investigational melanocortin
    agents, a selective <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> agonist.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>An oral peptide that doesn't need to be absorbed</h2>
  <p>
    The clever part is the delivery. Peptides are usually poor oral drugs because the gut
    digests them before they can reach the bloodstream — but PL-8177 turns that problem
    into a non-issue by <em>not trying to reach the bloodstream at all</em>. It is
    formulated to act locally, delivering the peptide to the lining of the colon, where in
    early testing it produced sustained colonic exposure with essentially no systemic
    absorption.<Cite n={2} /> Because its target — MC1R on the colon's epithelial cells — is
    right there in the gut, staying in the gut is a feature, not a failure. It is the
    exception that clarifies the rule: oral peptides struggle when they need to travel,
    not when they act where they land.
  </p>

  <h2>The ulcerative colitis signal</h2>
  <p>
    PL-8177's lead program is in <strong>ulcerative colitis</strong>, an inflammatory
    disease of the colon. A Phase 2 study of once-daily oral PL-8177 in active disease
    reported positive topline signals for clinical remission and response.<Cite n={1} /> The
    honest caveat matters, though: Palatin stopped enrollment early — at 12 patients rather
    than the larger planned cohort — as it redirected resources toward its melanocortin
    obesity programs and out-licensing discussions.<Cite n={2} /> With those numbers the study
    was not powered to demonstrate statistical significance, so the result is an
    encouraging signal rather than proof.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    PL-8177 is early, and its own developer has shifted focus, so its future is uncertain.
    But it is a clean illustration of the melanocortin system's anti-inflammatory arm being
    engineered into a drug — and of a smart way around the oral-peptide problem when the
    target sits in the gut. For the biology it draws on, see
    <a href="/alpha-msh">α-MSH</a>; for where it sits among everything in development, see
    the <a href="/pipeline">melanocortin pipeline</a>.
  </p>

